76561198007300752,Not Recommended,271360,33233254,Posted: 4 July,all,Blackadar,"I think there's probably a game here somewhere. I can't find it past the bugs and the noise however.Industry Giant 2 is an old-school tycoon type game. Don't let the release date fool you. This game came out in 2002 and was a bit dated even back then. I can get by the graphics even if it does take a fair amount of squinting. That's not the issue.The issue is the ""quality of life"" improvements that we've seen these 15 years are not reflected in the game. For instance, getting something as simple as milk from one place to another takes the following steps:1. Build cattle farm2. Go into cattle farm and select milk3. Build warehouse near farm4. Build truck depot near farm5. Build market near destination city6. Build warehouse near destination city, making sure it's within the market radius7. Build truck depot near destination city, making sure it's within the warehouse radius8. Build road to connect the farm depot with the city depot, making sure to connect the exits on both of the truck depots that are often hidden by the header over the depot (and you can't rotate the map)9. Go to the farm depot, click to choose the type of truck, hit accept10. Go to the next screen, tell it what you want to collect and whether it waits until it is full to run the route11. Click on the destination depotIf you've managed to do all of this correctly - and often the game gives an error - then your little truck will pick up milk and drive it to the destination city. Then there's the fiddling with the price, quantity supplied, amount produced, etc.*phew*  That's a bunch of steps! If that kind of micromanagement doesn't bother you then this might be your type of game. It kind of is my type as well.But then there are the numerous bugs. There are your normal lockup/crash type issues here but sometimes the game glitches and entirely screws you over. For instance, on the very first scenario I did the following steps. For some reason the AI decided it was a good idea to have other cars use my dirt road which terminated at my truck depot. They wouldn't move and the line of AI cars kept getting bigger and bigger which prevented my trucks from reaching the depot. With no way to remove the cars, I had to restart the scenario and there wasn't any part of that which was my fauilt. That's just the game deciding to take a dump on my scenario. Then the next time through it crashed and I lost what progress I had made. This does not make Blackadar happy.Then there are the QoL improvements that I spoke of earlier. The devs decided that bird noises were the best way to fill players' speakers and thus be prepared to here a cacophony of bird and other noises piercing your airspace. The interface is simply too small in spots and trying to see what you're doing can be difficult. You can't rotate the map and getting to certain spots or even buildings can be difficult - and this matters when you're trying to link up tracks/roads and so forth. It's an older game and there's been nothing done to bring it up to today's UI standards. Then there's the income statement which only shows per YEAR which means it's very difficult to figure out whether you've turned things around or not. Losing money and made some adjustments? Well, you're not going to be able to tell because there's no monthly income statement! That's a pretty massive oversight in a business sim.I might load this up again someday and see if it will work. But in the meanwhile, I've been unable to get through the very first scenario because it's simply not very stable. And even if I could get through it, I'm not sure if it's worth the effort. That's the issue here and the reason I can't recommend this game."
